Sup ya’ll 👋🏽 After strong feedback and suggestions from friends and family, I’ve created this profile to share my creative content. 

⚠️Warning - Here, I will share some of my favorite foods but I will rant about the many things I am passionate about. For I am a strong believer that the “food” you EAT affects your GROWTH📈 and DEVELOPMENT🧠. I hope you will enjoy the dialogue and eat with me. 

Just a little introduction. I’m a 40-something, 🇵🇭 American, native San Franciscan. I am a US Marine Corps veteran, devoted husband, father, and follower of ✝️

I was a latch🔑 kid, born and raised in the working class area of the City🌁 bordering Daly City’s east side; the Outer Mission. I attended SF and DC public schools where Asians (especially Filipino) and Latinos together comprise almost 90% of the demographic. 

Why do I mention all this extra info? I am giving context of where I’m from and the paradigm of my upbringing. Furthermore, I want to acknowledge that my world view will not be consistent with everyone, including fellow San Franciscans. The City and the greater Bay Area is among the most diverse places in the world and should be respected as such. As you view my content, I suggest you keep this in mind for yourself and not expect any different. 

With that said, you should know “WE do call it Frisco” out here. And if you take offense to that then my content is certainly not for you.✌🏽

#sanfrancisco #blogger #bayareaeats #reels

It’s been a minute but one of my favorite cities to travel to was Paris. I was fortunate to be a regular visitor of this global city during a previous career. 

Since the 17th century, Paris has been one of the world’s major centers of finance, diplomacy, commerce, fashion, gastronomy, and science. As an Asian-American I especially loved how I could throw on a scarf and some decently fashionable clothes and I would blend right in with the culture. Locals would actually approach and talk to me like I was French and be very accommodating and helpful when they found out I was American and couldn’t speak a lick of French. 😂

The funny thing is a colleague had told me before I traveled here that he found Parisians to be very rude, but it was the complete opposite for me in my brief interactions with the people. For instance, my friends and I wanted to try a doner kebab (similar to what we call a shawarma). A kebab in Euro culture is similar to a burrito in Frisco culture. While partying in the Latin Quarter, the locals we asked about this were so amused by our request that they personally took us to their late night favorite spot and introduced us to all their friends. And yes, the kebab lived up to the hype forreal. I wish I could find a pic! 😋

If you’ve been to Paris or plan to travel there one day, drop a comment below. I’d like to hear about it. 

📍Arch de Triomphe, Pl Charles de Gaulle, 75008 Paris, France, 2014

💫Throwback Thursday: “From 1998 to the early 2000s, I proudly served in the US Marine Corps, spending much of that time in San Diego, CA. The cultural contrasts between San Diego and San Francisco were especially vivid among Filipino-Americans. We shared commonalities, but our differences were undeniably pronounced. Just look at the fashion contrast between my cousins and me. I once even gave my San Diego homeboy, David, a fashion makeover just so we could lightweight match when we went out. Occasionally, I’d have to clarify certain “Frisco” phrases I used to my San Diego crew. My slang and mannerisms often gave away that I wasn’t from around there. Fast forward to today, and globalized fashion makes such distinctions harder to spot. But San Diego shaped me profoundly – as a person, a parent, and a professional. Those moments? Priceless. And here’s a little story - I met my wife at a house party in SD. She made the first move, a blessing I cherish and boast about regularly. I often wonder if her approach was sparked by my obvious differences from the local crew, or if I was just that good looking 😂. It’s all in the perspective. Our unique traits truly do work together for our good. My message today is CELEBRATE our differences! 🌟”

“Crunchy, Tasty, HELLA Bomb: Home-Made 🇵🇭 Chicharon Bulaklak in an Air Fryer! 😋”

When my cousin @archkitz, who’s from San Diego, found out that I’m a big fan of this particular Filipino dish, he offered to cook some for me. He mentioned that his cooking method was simple yet made the dish even more delicious. True to his word, it was absolutely CRACK!

I’d love to hear from you! Drop a comment below with your thoughts, tips, or even your own experiences with Filipino cuisine. Let’s chat and share our culinary adventures! 🍽️💬

Chicharon bulaklak (pork grind flowers) is a traditional Filipino appetizer known for its distinctive, rich flavor and crunchy texture. It is made from deep-fried ruffled fat, which is the membrane surrounding the pig’s intestines, cleaned thoroughly before cooking. This dish is often served with “sawsawan” which is a dipping sauce made of spicy vinegar. Chicharon bulaklak is popular as a pulutan (food eaten with alcoholic drinks), often accompanied by a cold beer, and is a staple at Filipino gatherings and celebrations.

👨🏽‍🍳 @archkitz 🫡

📝Preparation:

Chicharon bulaklak is boiled 45-60 min prior. Drain, then air fry. Sprinkle with sinigang powder mix for seasoning. 

“Sawsawan” (dipping sauce) shown is made of spicy vinegar, garlic, onions (optional), ground pepper, crushed red pepper, and sugar.

✍🏼 In the 1700s, Spanish miners extracted limestone for San Francisco’s Presidio buildings. In 1888, Stefano Mori, an Italian immigrant, acquired 19 acres. He erected the Mori Point Inn, a notorious hub during Prohibition, operating under the family until the 1940s.

World War II transformed Mori Point into a gravel and sand extraction site, leaving visible scars from quarrying and off-road vehicle use. The turn of the century brought change. With support from the Pacifica Land Trust, Coastal Conservancy, and the community, Trust for Public Land acquired Mori Point in 2000, seamlessly integrating it into the Golden Gate National Parks.
